{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0,0.57,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7465"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67870"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7465"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5157"},{"type":"tags","id":"7631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22723"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67870"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with multiple small, flesh-coloured lesions on her external genitalia (Image). After examination confirms genital warts, or more correctly condylomata accuminata, she is prescribed podophyllotoxin solution for topical application.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of this agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activates apoptosis receptors","Blocks sodium channels","Disrupts viral protein synthesis","Inhibits DNA polymerase","Prevents microtubule assembly"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECondylomata accuminata are a type of sexually transmitted infection (STI), where the infectious agent is the human papillomavirus (HPV). Podophyllotoxin is an antimitotic agent that works by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing microtubule assembly\u003C/strong\u003E. This causes cells to arrest in metaphase of the cell cycle, preventing further division of rapidly proliferating cells like those in genital warts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt does not primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting DNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivating apoptosis receptors\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003Edisrupting viral protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E. While some of these effects may occur secondarily, the main therapeutic action is through microtubule disruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPodophyllotoxin is derived from the mayapple plant (\u003Cem\u003EPodophyllum peltatum\u003C/em\u003E) and is used as a topical treatment for genital warts caused by human papillomavirus infection. Its mechanism is similar to other plant-derived antimitotic agents like colchicine and vincristine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Podophyllotoxin works by preventing microtubule assembly and arresting cell division in metaphase.","Podophyllotoxin is used topically to treat genital warts caused by human papillomavirus.","Podophyllotoxin is derived from the mayapple plant (Podophyllum peltatum)."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21292"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21292"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XBil1MiYrfR3H7fkEvr6AUNS8cDjDB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XBil1MiYrfR3H7fkEvr6AUNS8cDjDB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":298,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T15:31:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T15:33:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7465"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67870"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description"